32 Indian fishermen feared to be detained by British Navy on Diego Garcia 
5-3-2017 
MADURAI: As many as 32 fishermen hailing from Tamil Nadu and Kerala are feared to be detained in British Indian Ocean Territory of Diego Garcia According to fishermen sources, deep sea fishing boats Al-Ameen with the registration number KL04/MM/2199 and Mermaid with the registration number TN15/MM/5326 and their crew members have been detained on Diego Garcia since March 1.Al-Ameen is owned by K S Hussain and had 15 crew members of whom six are from Thoothoor in Kanyakumari district of Tamil Nadu and the rest are from Poonthurai, Vizhinjam and Ernakulam in Kerala.Mermaid is owned by Judy Albert and it had 17 crew members in which eight are from Thoothoor and the rest are from Puthiathurai, Pulluvilai, Vizhingam and Parasala in Kerala.The deep sea fishing boats sailed from Kochi on February 5 and were supposed to return after a month-long fishing expedition."We have learnt that these two fishing vessels are held on Diego Garcia - 1,500 nautical miles off the India coast - and the families of fishermen are worried. We have informed local fisheries officials and are planning to submit a petition to district administration on Monday," said Thoothoor Deep Sea Fishermen Cooperative Society president Jose Bilbin.Fisheries officials said they were yet to get an official confirmation. "Fishermen have informed us that two of fishing boats have been detained by the British Navy in British Indian Ocean Territory of Diego Garcia. We are waiting for the official confirmation from the central government", said deputy director of fisheries (Kanyakumari) Lamek Jayakumar. 
